<div id="review_3613480936" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3613480936" />
    <a title="Swaroop" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/100264072-swaroop"><img alt="Swaroop" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621672092p2/100264072.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3613480936?book_show_action=true">Nov 12, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Swaroop" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Swaroop" href="/user/show/100264072-swaroop">Swaroop</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3613480936" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14591907919359169170">The story of an English lecturer in the town of <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malgudi' rel='nofollow noopener'>Malgudi</a> - his love for his wife and quest for inner peace!<br/><br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1605862654i/30402617.jpg' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/5213496.Rasupuram_K__Narayan' title='Rasupuram K. Narayan' rel='nofollow noopener'>R K Narayan</a> takes me on an interesting and engaging journey - into the life of an English teacher, Krishna. It feels, and starts as a simple account about a teacher (reminded me of <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2906292211' rel='nofollow noopener'>William Stoner</a> of John Williams), but then an immense tragedy hits Krishna`s life, and everything changes.<br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1605864373i/30402711._SY540_.jpg' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/><i>&quot;After the car had gone, a stony silence closed in on the house, punctuated by the stentorian breathing, wh</i></span>
  <span id="freeText14591907919359169170" style="display:none">The story of an English lecturer in the town of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malgudi" rel="nofollow noopener">Malgudi</a> - his love for his wife and quest for inner peace!<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1605862654i/30402617.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/5213496.Rasupuram_K__Narayan" title="Rasupuram K. Narayan" rel="nofollow noopener">R K Narayan</a> takes me on an interesting and engaging journey - into the life of an English teacher, Krishna. It feels, and starts as a simple account about a teacher (reminded me of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2906292211" rel="nofollow noopener">William Stoner</a> of John Williams), but then an immense tragedy hits Krishna`s life, and everything changes.<br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1605864373i/30402711._SY540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><i>"After the car had gone, a stony silence closed in on the house, punctuated by the stentorian breathing, which appeared to me the creaking of the hinges of a prison gate, opening at the command of a soul going into freedom."</i> <br><br>The writing is simple, yet so beautifully expressive - <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/5213496.Rasupuram_K__Narayan" title="Rasupuram K. Narayan" rel="nofollow noopener">R K Narayan</a> narrates the tragedy and loss in such a subtle way that I had to read those last few chapters again, just to understand and realise that it really happened.<br><br><i>"There are no more surprises and shocks in life, so that I can watch the flame without agitation. For me the greatest reality is this and nothing else... Nothing else will worry or interest me in life hereafter."</i><br><br><i>"- but our nature adapts itself to circumstances with wonderful speed."</i><br><br>After the tragedy, the storyline feels a wee bit far-fetched, but then the author stated this book is autobiographical and from personal experiences, and is dedicated to his wife.<br><br><i>"I imagined, even as I spoke, how she would touch the marble of Taj, stand astounded before the snow-covered Himalayas, and before the crowd and magnitude of European cities."</i> <br><br><i>"These tiny phials had compressed in them the essence of her personality, the rustle of her dress, her footfalls, laughter, her voice, and the light in her eyes, the perfume of her presence."</i><br><blockquote>
  <i>"The fact must be recognised. <b>A profound unmitigated loneliness is the only truth of life. All else is false.</b>"</i>
</blockquote></span>
  <a data-text-id="14591907919359169170" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


